List MATOS projects

Source: R/list_projects.R
list_projects.Rd

This function scrapes the table found at https://matos.asascience.com/project and combines it with project metadata stored on the Ocean Tracking Network Geoserver. This table provides the full name of the project, collection code, MATOS project number, MATOS project page URL, project status, full name, citation, website, project type, area, and abstract. You do not need to log in via matos_login or have any permissions to view/download this table.

Usage

list_projects(
  what = c("all", "mine"),
  read_access = TRUE,
  quiet = FALSE,
  force = FALSE
)

Arguments

what

What list of projects do you want returned: all projects ("all", default) or your projects ("mine")?

read_access

If listing your projects, do you want to only list projects for which you have file-read permission? Defaults to TRUE, though there is significant speed up if switched to FALSE.

quiet

Do you want to suppress messages regarding matched projects? Defaults to FALSE.

force

Do you want to reset the cache and re-ping the database? Defaults to false.

Examples

list_projects()

#> 6                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        Rapid growth of the wind energy industry on the US OCS has increased vessel traffic in offshore waters. This study considers the ecological role of large-bodied, low-tropic level marine species (i.e., basking shark, Cetorhinus maximus; ocean sunfish, Mola mola) and potential risks to the species from offshore wind (OSW) energy development. Data are gathered using a variety of technologies (acoustic tags, camera tags) and acoustic receivers are deployed by commercial fishing partners around the island of Martha's Vineyard, MA.
#> 7          The mid-Atlantic continental shelf has been identified by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory as the coastal region with the greatest offshore wind resource potential in waters less than 60 m deep and therefore is very well suited for near-term offshore wind energy technology. Federally endangered Atlantic Sturgeon (Acipenser oxyrinchus oxyrinchus) and the commercially important Winter Skate (Leucoraja ocellata), are two species that occur in the Delaware Wind Energy Area (WEA), although there is little information on their patterns of residency and habitat. Acoustic receivers were deployed around the perimeter of the DE WEA in February 2017 to monitor the seasonal occupancy and movement of telemetered individuals. In April 2017, VEMCO acoustic transmitters were implanted in 50 Atlantic Sturgeon, and 50 Winter Skate in the Delaware coastal ocean. In addition, the receivers record the presence of species tagged with compatible transmitters identified through the ACT network.
#> 8              Sandbridge Shoal is a borrow area off of Virginia that is used by multiple stakeholders to rebuild beaches. This area has also been identified as an Essential Fish Habitat (EFH) for many species, including 8 sharks characterized as Highly Migratory Species (HMS). As information about the use of the borrow area by migratory sharks is scarce, and dredging activities are expected to continue during the next few years, research efforts to improve the comprehension of the ecology of these large predators will increase our understanding of the potential effects of dredging and contribute to the eventual implementation of adapted mitigation measures. Similar research is also conducted in a similar shoal (Hens and Chickens Shoal in Delaware) where dredging activities are not conducted. A total of 15 VR2AR VEMCO receivers have been deployed to cover Sandridge Shoal and at least 25 acoustic transmitters are aimed to be deployed on individuals of various shark species in 2022 and 2023.

#> 13                                                                                                                        Mount Desert Rock, located roughly 20 miles offshore of Mount Desert Island in the Gulf of Maine, is a highly biologically productive zone that supports a large colony of gray seals (Halichoerus grypus) and harbor seals (Phoca vitulina). Evidence of predation in the form of shark bites on seals hauled out on the Rock has provided some insight into the presence of white sharks (Carcharodon carcharias) and mako sharks (Isurus oxyrinchus) but much remains to be studied on the population dynamics and behaviors of sharks in the area. This project aims to document the presence and absence of tagged sharks in the waters surrounding Mount Desert Rock as well as shifts in populations in response to changing environmental factors. In collaboration with the College of the Atlantic and Allied Whale, one VEMCO VR2W acoustic receiver was deployed in the waters near Mount Desert Rock.

#> 22            Southern flounder (Paralichthys lethostigma) is an economically important species throughout its range, but it is overfished in North Carolina and the southeastern USA.  Offshore spawning grounds have not been identified for southern flounder populations in any state. Our objectives are to: (1) Determine the timing of offshore migration by acoustically tagging southern flounder in North Carolina and monitoring when they pass through acoustic gates spanning all inlets in Pamlico Sound; (2) Track offshore migrations of tagged flounder and locate possible spawning grounds by using an offshore acoustic curtain and an autonomous vehicle (wave glider with telemetry receiver); (3) Conduct ichthyoplankton surveys at potential spawning sites and use DNA barcoding to determine if southern flounder eggs are found; (4) Determine sex and maturity of adults sampled offshore; (5) Back calculate the location of potential spawning habitats of southern flounder by aging larval flounder caught.

#> 25               The Ørsted Ecosystem and Passive Acoustic Monitoring (ECO-PAM) project is a partnership between Ørsted North America, Rutgers U., Woods Hole Oceanographic, and the U. of Rhode Island. ECO-PAM aims to advance research for detection of N. Atl. right whale, to better understand their presence, distribution, and seasonality, and to contribute to characterization of their habitat in offshore wind lease areas. ECO-PAM will be focused on the Ørsted Ocean Wind lease area off of NJ but will also include sampling in Ørsted lease areas around MA. The project will include two acoustic monitoring buoys deployed by WHOI, an acoustic vector sensor buoy developed by URI, and an autonomous underwater glider deployed by RU. Results will be used to inform and mitigate impacts during construction and operation of offshore wind facilities. In addition to the passive acoustics used to detect whales, gliders will be equipped with VEMCO receivers to detect tagged fish along the glider trajectory.
#> 26                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           This study was initiated to test the viability of working with citizen scientists to collect acoustic telemetry data.  Recreational mariners sailing on extensive cruises along a variety of national coastal waterways, were assigned to carry VEMCO VR2W receivers and asked to deploy the receivers from their boats each time they docked or anchored. The study aimed to determine if this method had the potential to record tagged fish and fill gaps in stationary receiver array coverage. Results indicated that these deployments were not only effective in detecting tagged fish and complementing stationary receiver arrays, but may also function as a method for determining positioning of future stationary receiver arrays.
#> 27                                                                                                                     The Hudson River presumably supports the largest population shortnose sturgeon as observed throughout its range based on three population estimates conducted in the 1970's and 1990's.  Between these estimates, the population increased quickly, far exceeding ESA recovery criteria.  All three estimates were calculated from traditional mark/recapture study designs which require a large amount of effort, are costly, are often biased and have large error associated due to the violation of assumptions. The goal of the study is to integrate high resolution side-scan sonar, acoustic telemetry, and targeted sampling of adults to develop multi-year quantitative population estimates for shortnose sturgeon in the Hudson River. The abundance estimates will be used to help set and track recovery objectives and criteria, a top priority identified by the National Marine Fisheries Service.

#> 39                                                          The Mallows Bay-Potomac River National Marine Sanctuary (MPNMS) is an 18-square mile sanctuary located in the Potomac River of the Chesapeake Bay. #> 55                                      The North Carolina Division of Marine Fisheries (NCDMF) in partnership with the National Marine Fisheries Service conducted a study to determine which river basins are used by American shad (Alosa sapidissima) during spawning runs in the Albemarle Sound. American shad were captured in the Albemarle Sound, tagged with sonic transmitters, and their spawning migrations were tracked using an array of acoustic receivers. Of the 62 fish which made detectable migrations during the six years of the study, 55 ascended the Chowan River while only five ascended the Roanoke River. These results indicate the Albemarle Sound stock of American shad prefer the spawning grounds in the Chowan and its tributaries, the Blackwater, Nottoway, and Meherrin rivers over those in the Roanoke River. This project contains only tagging data for American Shad tagged in this study. For acoustic telemetry array information, see the associated NCDMF waterbody array project in MATOS.

#> 146                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               Non-native Blue Catfish (Ictalurus furcatus) were intentionally introduced into the James River in the 1970’s to create a recreational fishery. #> 147                                 Bowfin, Amia calva, is an evolutionarily and ecologically important species native to much of eastern North America. It is a large bodied (to 700+ mm TL) generalist apex predator in many river systems. Relatively little is known about the spatial ecology of Bowfin, with only a single study published using acoustic telemetry to determine habitat use  (from Lake Ontario; Midwood et al. 2018). Northern Snakehead, native to eastern Asia, is an established, invasive species in tributaries of the Chesapeake Bay in Maryland and Virginia. It is morphologically and ecologically similar to Bowfin. Beyond its occurrence in the tributaries, little is known of aspects of its ecology in these rivers. This study will employ acoustic telemetry to fill in these data gaps so that habitat use, movement patterns, temperature selectivity, and environmental responses of bowfin and snakehead can be assessed and compared in a tidal freshwater habitat in the mid-Atlantic region.
#> 148                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Spotted Seatrout (also known as Speckled Trout) is the focus of an important recreational fishery in the southeastern United States. Virginia is the northern extent of speckled trout populations and is the most likely portion of its range to experience cold-stun events. The primary objective of this project was to use acoustic telemetry fitted with internal temperature loggers to better understand how speckled trout react to declining water temperatures and begin to assess what proportion of the population is subject to cold stun events.
